<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-825-658  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 825 658.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Oct 30 1989 v6 n43 p159(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Improved earnings spell recovery for drive industry.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Burke, Steven.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Micropolis Corp. (earnings)Conner Peripherals (earnings).andO;Ticker:    MLIS.andO;Topic:     Disk Drivesm ProfitGrowthIndustry Analysis3.5&quot; DiskInvestments.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Steven BurkeandM;MONTEREY, CALIF.andP;  -- The financial picture is looking brighter for thetroubled disk-drive industry.andM;In stark contrast to the grim note of last year's statements, there was amore positive tone to the earnings reports and forecasts presented bydisk-drive makers here last week at the American Electronics Associationfinancial conference.andM;Officials from even the most battered firms said the worst is behind theindustry, which was in a severe tailspin last year.andP;  That downturn, sparkedby a price war and excess capacity and inventory, has brought about dramaticchanges at many firms and a more sober, mature market.andM;&quot;We're sadder and wiser,&quot; said Stuart Mabon, president of Micropolis Corp. ofChatsworth, Calif.andP;  The firm, which lost $67 million in the last fivequarters, has implemented internal controls to make sure it doesn't sufferthe same fate again.andM;After announcing a loss of $23.7 million for its third quarter ended Sept.andO;30, Micropolis expects to post only a slight loss or to break even in thefourth quarter.andM;Gone are the days of price cuts and grabbing for market share at the expenseof profitability, said industry executives.andM;&quot;It's a more stable and predictable industry,&quot; said Finis Conner, chairman ofConner Peripherals Inc., of San Jose, Calif.andP;  The major stabilizing factorsare improved long-term management controls and better pricing, he said.andM;Conner last week reported that earnings for its third quarter, ended Sept.andO;30, were up 72 percent to $11.8 million.andP;  Sales were up 172 percent to $184million.andM;Most disk-drive makers have improved the bottom line by investing in thehigh-growth 3-1/2-inch disk-drive market.andM;That's the story at Komag Inc., a Milpitas, Calif., supplier of thin-filmdisks to disk-drive makers.andP;  The company earned $915,000 for the quarterended Oct.andP;  1 after posting a loss of $1.6 million in the previous quarter.andO;Revenue for 3-1/2-inch media jumped from nothing to more than 20 percent ofits business for the quarter.andM;One of the most dramatic rebounds has been at Seagate Technology, which leadsthe 5-1/4- and 3-1/2-inch disk-drive market with a 40 percent market share.andO;In the third quarter last year, Seagate reported a $52.8 million loss.andP;  Thisyear, the Scotts Valley, Calif., firm reported it earned $23.4 million onrecord sales of $378.8 million.andO;</TEXT></DOC>